Analyzing Customer Service for ABC Inc.¶

Analysis by Animish Andraskar

In this analysis, we are trying to find out answers to some questions that would help ABC Inc. understand the characteristics of customer service they provide, and know the key areas of improvement.

The data provided for this assignment is a sanitized subset of an actual customer service data. The purpose of this assignment was to answer some preset and some additional questions through exploratory data analysis.

The data has following columns:

  • asst_id: Unique identifier of an asset
  • product_type: Category of the asset
  • mnfture_wk: Year and week in which the asset was manufactured
  • contract_st: Year and week when the contract (warranty service from ABC Inc.) started
  • contract_end: Year and week when the contract ended
  • contact_wk: Year and week when customer contacted ABC's service center
  • contact_type: Mode of contact used by the customer
  • issue_type: Issue defined by the customer
  • topic_category: Issue identified by the agent
  • parts_sent: Names of the parts sent when the customer contacted for the first time
  • parts_ct: Number of parts sent on first contact
  • repair_type: Whether the repair needed hardware (hard) or software (soft) to fix the issue. In case both, it is categorized as hard.
  • repeat_parts_sent: Names of the parts sent when the customer contacted again for the same issue
  • repeat_ct: Number of parts sent when the customer contacted again for the same issue
  • agent_tenure_indays: Tenure of the agent who handled the request (in days)
  • contact_manager_flg: Flag whether agent needed help from his/her manager
  • diagnostics: Company's internal diagnostics measures used by the agent
  • region: Region of the asset sale (not necessarily the current customer location)
  • country: Country of the asset sale (not necessarily the current customer location)

def get_value_counts(string):
    """
    This function takes in a string and splits it on " ," to separate out atomic values in it.
    Then, it finds the count enclosed within parantheses.
    For example,
    if we have a string "Hard Drive, Documentation(2)", it will provide Hard Drive with count 1
    and Documentation with count 2.
    """
    # split string on " ,"
    st_split = str(string).split(", ")
    
    # empty list to hold value and count
    value_counts = []
    # set to hold unique values extracted
    values = set()
    
    # traverse each split element from the string
    for sts_split in st_split:
        # if the split part contains parantheses AND those parantheses include only numbers
        if sts_split.count("(") >= 1 and re.match("^[0-9)]*$", sts_split.rsplit('(', maxsplit=1)[1]):
            # split the string from right, so that we get 2 from strings like "Battery (Notebook)(2)"
            ssp_split = sts_split.rsplit('(', maxsplit=1)
            # remove spaces and convert to lowercase
            val = ssp_split[0].replace(" ", "").lower()
            # after trimming, if the value is null, skip
            # otherwise, note down the value and its count
            if val != "nan" and val != "":
                cnt = int(ssp_split[1].replace(")", ""))
                value_counts.append((val, cnt))
                values.add(val)
        # if no parantheses or only numbers inside parantheses, simply take the value and count is 1
        else:
            val = sts_split.replace(" ", "").lower()
            if val != "nan" and val != "":
                value_counts.append((val, 1))
                values.add(val)
    return values, value_counts

def create_value_counts(col, suffix, create_new=True):
    """
    This function takes the column name to create new columns on and a suffix to add to those columns names.
    For example, if we are separating out values inside issue_type, we would pass the name as the first argument,
    and issue_ as the suffix.
    """
    # unique values, and value-count pairs to be returned by get_value_counts()
    values = set() # this will help us in creating new columns
    value_counts = [] # this will help us in adding the counts in those columns
    
    # traverse each row, split the string inside it to get the value and its count enclosed in parantheses
    for row in explore_data[col]:
        vals, value_ct = get_value_counts(row)
        # add value to our unique values set
        values.update(vals)
        # add value-count to the list
        value_counts.append(value_ct)
        
#     at this point, values should have all the unique split values
#     and value_counts should have elements equal to number of rows in the dataset

#        if we have three rows:
#             Miscellaneous(2)
#             Motherboard, Documentation(ABC)(2)
#             Motherboard, Documentation

#.       values will be a set of {"Miscellaneous", "Motherboard", "Documentation" and "Documentation(ABC)"}

#.       value_counts will have 3 sub-lists (one for each row):
#.             [
#                 [("Miscellaneous", 1)],
#                 [("Motherboard", 1), ("Documentation(ABC)", 2)],
#                 [("Motherboard", 1), ("Documentation", 1)]
#              ]

#       Documentation and Documentation(ABC) are treated different
        
    print("Total columns created:", len(values))

    # for each unique extracted value, create a new column in the data if the flag set to true
    if create_new:
        # first, create a list of column names with suffix for later use
        # then, create those columns with count "0"
        new_cols = []
        for val in values:
            new_cols.append(suffix + val)
            explore_data[suffix + val] = 0
        # store new column names in a dictionary
        created_value_counts[col] = new_cols

    # Update counts form value_counts
    for i, vc_all in enumerate(value_counts):
        for vc in vc_all: # traverse each value count pair in each row. Some rows may have no value counts (originally null)
            explore_data.loc[i, suffix + vc[0]] += vc[1]

def plot_top_n(col, n=20, display_n=10, explore_data=explore_data):
    """
    This function displays top "n" most frequently occurring values in a column "col",
    and also prints top "display_n" most frequently occurring values with counts
    """
    # get unique values from the column
    value_count_all  = explore_data[col].value_counts()
    # keep only top n
    value_count = value_count_all[:n,]
    # display display_n values
    display(value_count_all[:display_n,])
    
    # plot
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
    sns.barplot(value_count.values, value_count.index, alpha=0.8, orient='h')
    plt.title("Top " + str(n) + " frequently occurring values in \"" + col + "\"")
    plt.ylabel("Values", fontsize=12)
    plt.xlabel("Count", fontsize=12)
    plt.show()

def get_top_n_from_split(col, subset_by=None, subset_val=None, n=None, explore_data=explore_data):
    """
    This function gets top "n" most frequently occurring values, but from the
    new columns we ccreated after extracting comma delimited values from composite columns.
    This function can also subset the columns like count only for product_type="Laptops"
    """
    # if both subset column and subset value are present
    if subset_by != None and subset_val != None:
        # subset the data based on condition
        explore_data = explore_data[explore_data[subset_by] == subset_val]
    
    # to hold every column's sum
    col_counts = {}
    # traverse through the list of all columns we created for the composit column "col"
    for c in created_value_counts[col]:
        # get the sum of that column
        col_counts[c] = explore_data[c].sum()
    # now sort the column sum, and display the column name
    #.   note that each column name is an actual value in the original column
    value_count = pd.Series(col_counts).sort_values(ascending=False)
    
    # if n defined, keep only top n
    if n != None:
        value_count = value_count[:n,]
        
    return value_count

def plot_top_n_from_split(col, subset_by=None, subset_val=None, n=20, display_n=10, explore_data=explore_data):
    """
    This function plots the top n derived values from the composit column given by get_top_n_from_split()
    """
    
    # Get value counts
    value_count = get_top_n_from_split(col, subset_by=subset_by, subset_val=subset_val)
    
    # display top display_n values
    display(value_count[:display_n,])
    
    # we do not pass n to get_top_n_from_split() because display_n can be greater than n and the function might fail.
    # hence keep only top n values now
    value_count = value_count[:n,]
    
    # plot
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
    sns.barplot(value_count.values, value_count.index, alpha=0.8, orient='h')
    plt.title("Top " + str(n) + " frequently occurring values in split \"" + col + "\" values")
    plt.ylabel("Values", fontsize=12)
    plt.xlabel("Count", fontsize=12)
    plt.show()

def is_outlier(points, thresh=5):
    """
    Function to avoid x-axis of graphs from becoming unecessarily long by detecting if a value is an outlier.
    The default z-score is kept 5!
    """
    if len(points.shape) == 1:
        points = points[:,None]
    avg = np.mean(points, axis=0)
    diff = np.sum((points - avg)**2, axis=-1)
    diff = np.sqrt(diff)
    med_abs_deviation = np.mean(diff)

    modified_z_score = 0.6745 * diff / med_abs_deviation
    return modified_z_score > thresh

def plot_distribution(aggregate_col, count_col, explore_data=explore_data):
    """
    This function aggregates the counts of "count_col" for each value in "aggregate_col",
    and plots the distribution.
    For example,
    aggregate the counts for parts sent (count_col) by each asset type (aggregate_col)
    """
    # get unique values to aggregate on
    unique_values = list(explore_data[aggregate_col].unique())

    # number of columns
    ncols=3
    # number of rows are calculated automatically
    nrows=(len(unique_values)-1)//ncols+1
    # define subplot
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=nrows,ncols=ncols,figsize=(15,4*nrows), sharex=True)
    
    print("Distribution of \"" + count_col + "\" over \"" + aggregate_col + "\" values")
    
    # traverse and plot each subplot
    i = j = 0
    for val in unique_values:
        if nrows == 1: # if only 1 row, only 1 index
            ax = axes[j,]
        else:
            ax = axes[i, j]
        # get counts for the value
        counts = explore_data[explore_data[aggregate_col] == val][count_col]
        # plot
        ax.title.set_text(val)
        ax.tick_params(labelbottom=True)
        ax.hist(counts[~is_outlier(counts)], label=val, alpha=0.8)
        # increment counts
        j += 1
        if j == ncols: # if end of the row, reset j and increment i
            i += 1
            j = 0
            
    # if we have empty graphs
    # this occurs when we have, say, 8 plots and the grid is 3x3
    # in that case, we will have a blank plot on (3,3)
    if len(unique_values) < ncols*nrows:
        flatax = axes.flatten()
        for k in range(ncols*nrows-len(unique_values)):
            if nrows != 1: # if only 1 row, only 1 index
                fig.delaxes(axes[i, -(k+1)])
            else:
                fig.delaxes(axes[-(k+1)])

    plt.show()

def do_t_test(aggregate_col, count_col, valpairs, explore_data=explore_data, alpha=0.05):
    """
    This function does t-test to test the difference in means of counts of "count_col"
    across values in "aggregate_col". These values need to be manually paired and passed via valpairs.
    """
    unique_vals = list(explore_data[aggregate_col].unique())
    
    # traverse each value pair
    for (val1, val2) in valpairs:
        # get counts for both the values
        val1_ct = explore_data[explore_data[aggregate_col] == val1].dropna()[count_col]
        val2_ct = explore_data[explore_data[aggregate_col] == val2].dropna()[count_col]
        # get t-statistic
        t, p = stats.ttest_ind(val1_ct, val2_ct)
        
        # print statistic and the result
        print("T-test for difference in mean '" + count_col +"' across '" + str(val1) + "' and '" + str(val2) + "' in " + aggregate_col)
        print("Mean for ('" + str(val1) + "'):,", val1_ct.mean(), "    ", "Mean for ('" + str(val2) + "'):,", val2_ct.mean())
        
        print("  t = " + str(t))
        print("  p = " + str(p))
        if p <= alpha:
            print(" Significant difference")
        else:
            print(" No significant difference")
        print("_____")
        print("")
        print("")
In [32]:
def get_contingency_table(aggregate_col, count_col, explore_data=explore_data, df=True):
    """
    This function creates contingency table for chi-squared test.
    Both aggregate_col and count_col are categorical here.
    """
    # get unique values from the "aggregate_col" column
    aggregate_col_unique = list(explore_data[aggregate_col].unique())
    # get unique values from the "count_col" column
    count_col_unique = list(explore_data[count_col].unique())
    
    # keep a trac of row and column names of the contingency table
    contingency_colnames = []
    contingency_rownames = []
    
    # contingency table is a list of lists
    contingency_table = []
    
    for c in count_col_unique:
        contingency_colnames.append(c) # columns will be each value we are finding counts for
        
    for a in aggregate_col_unique:
        contingency_row = []
        contingency_rownames.append(a) # row indices will be each value we are aggregating on
        for c in count_col_unique:
            # append the counts to the row for aggregated value
            contingency_row.append(
                explore_data[(explore_data[aggregate_col]==a) & (explore_data[count_col]==c)].shape[0]
            ) 
        contingency_table.append(contingency_row)
        
    # if output to be returned in pd.DataFrame
    if df:
        return pd.DataFrame(contingency_table, columns=contingency_colnames, index=contingency_rownames)
    else: # else, return the list of lists, row names and column names separately
        return contingency_table, contingency_rownames, contingency_colnames
In [33]:
def get_chi_sq_results(table, alpha=0.025):
    """
    This function performs chi-squared test on the contingency table and prints the results.
    """
    # Reference: https://machinelearningmastery.com/chi-squared-test-for-machine-learning/
    stat, p, dof, expected = chi2_contingency(table, correction=False)
    print("")
    print("Actual:")
    print(pd.DataFrame(table))
    print("")
    print("Expected:")
    print(pd.DataFrame(expected, columns=table.columns, index=table.index).round().astype(object))
    print("")
    
    print('Degrees of freedom: %d' % dof)
    
    prob = 1-alpha
    critical = chi2.ppf(prob, dof)
    print('probability=%.3f, critical=%.3f, stat=%.3f' % (prob, critical, stat))
    if abs(stat) >= critical:
        print(' Different than expected (reject H0)')
    else:
        print(' Not different than expected (fail to reject H0)')
        
    print('significance=%.3f, p=%.3f' % (alpha, p))
    if p <= alpha:
        print(' Different than expected (reject H0)')
    else:
        print(' Not different than expected (fail to reject H0)')
        
    print("_____")
    print("")
    print("")
In [34]:
def do_chi_sq(aggregate_col, count_col, valgroups=None, cols=None, explore_data=explore_data, alpha=0.025):
    """
    This function handles chi-square tests for various values to aggregate on and find counts for.
    """
    # get the contingency table
    contingency_df = get_contingency_table(aggregate_col, count_col)
    if cols != None: # if we are keeping only some counts (like keep counts of only "VOICE" and "EMAIL" issues)
        contingency_df = contingency_df[cols]
        
    if valgroups == None:
        get_chi_sq_results(contingency_df, alpha=alpha)
    else: # if we are subsetting on values (like keep counts of only for "Laptops" and "Desktops")
        for vals in valgroups:
            print("Chi-squared test for counts of '" + count_col +"' across ", vals, " in " + aggregate_col)
            contingency_df_subset = contingency_df.loc[vals]
            # get result for each value set provided
            get_chi_sq_results(contingency_df_subset, alpha=alpha)

def plot_cat_distribution(aggregate_col, count_col, explore_data=explore_data, print_chisq=False):
    """
    This function plots the distribution of two categorical frequencies.
    aggregate_col and count_col are both categorical. We create the contingency table and plot it.
    """
    # get unique values to aggregate on
    unique_values = list(explore_data[aggregate_col].unique())
    
    # get its contingency table
    df = get_contingency_table(aggregate_col, count_col)

    # graphs will have 3 columns
    ncols=3
    # find number of rows automatically
    nrows=(len(unique_values)-1)//ncols+1
    # define subplot
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=nrows,ncols=ncols,figsize=(15,4*nrows), sharex=True)
    
    # plot each graph. very similar to plot_distribution() function above.
    print("Distribution of \"" + count_col + "\" over \"" + aggregate_col + "\" values")
    i = j = 0
    for val in unique_values:
        if nrows == 1: # if only 1 row, only 1 index
            ax = axes[j,]
        else:
            ax = axes[i, j]
        ax.title.set_text(str(val))
        ax.tick_params(labelbottom=True)
        ax.bar(df.columns, df.loc[val,])
        
        j += 1
        if j == ncols:
            i += 1
            j = 0
            
    # if we have empty graphs
    # this occurs when we have, say, 8 plots and the grid is 3x3
    # in that case, we will have a blank plot on (3,3)
    if len(unique_values) < ncols*nrows:
        flatax = axes.flatten()
        for k in range(ncols*nrows-len(unique_values)):
            if nrows != 1: # if only 1 row, only 1 index
                fig.delaxes(axes[i, -(k+1)])
            else:
                fig.delaxes(axes[-(k+1)])

    plt.show()
    
    # if we are printing chi-squared statistic along
    if print_chisq:
        do_chi_sq(aggregate_col, count_col)

3. Data analysis¶

3.1 Understanding service consumption¶

This data can answer several questions related to the consumption of the service. These questions would help in predicting the demand for service and its type.

  • Do customers owning different types of assets tend to contact in different times of the year? (all queries are from the same week)
  • Do repeat counts vary by contact types?
  • Does number of parts sent vary by contact types?
  • Does number of parts sent vary by asset types?
  • Do customers owning different types of assets tend to use different contact media?
  • Do issue types vary across different contact media?
  • Do topic categories vary across contact types?

Understanding how number of parts sent vary across different issue attributes¶

Purpose: to understand if certain areas have a high number of parts sent, to prepare better for handling future issues.
